tories in favourable directions, and that these new policies should be developed with respect to the life course considered as a whole. "Old age" is a slippery concept, and the effective boundaries between it and "middle age" are not always clear. The essays in Aging and Demographic Change in Canadian Context address these challenges and seek to broaden public discussion on aging and Canadian public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAge distribution (Demography)zCanada. 0aAgingxSocial aspectszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Krista, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheal, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheal, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcDaniel, Susan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorris, Joan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrager, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Marty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThorpe, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTindale, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenne, Rosemary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267073040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670730.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_E